<p class=3DMsoNormal><span lang=3DEN-GB style=3D'mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;ms=
o-no-proof:
yes'>In addition, you can always colonize any planet with a pre-existing al=
ien
population. However the existing population may resist your colonization
attempts, so this strategy has the risk of wasting your expensive colony sh=
ip
if colonization fails.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span lang=3DEN-GB style=3D'mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;ms=
o-no-proof:
yes'>If you successfully colonize a planet with a pre-existing alien
population, you may receive a bonus gift from these new citizens of your
empire.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h3><span lang=3DEN-GB>Planet Quality</span></h3>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span lang=3DEN-GB style=3D'mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;ms=
o-no-proof:
yes'>Note that each planet and moon has a Quality rating that indicates how
habitable it is. The highest quality planets are 100%. These should be prime
targets for colonization.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span lang=3DEN-GB style=3D'mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;ms=
o-no-proof:
yes'>However any planet or moon with a quality below 50% should be avoided.
These planets will be a net drain on your empire&#8217;s economy if you
colonize them. They will cost more to support than they produce in revenue.
There may be rare situations where you choose to colonize a planet with qua=
lity
less than 50% (e.g. has special resources), but beware of the negative affe=
ct
on your empire revenue.</span></p>

